habitat: Between two unpaved roads, within 100 yards of northern access road. Quercus laurifolia is the primary canopy cover. Cornus sp. and Vaccinium fuscatum found intermittently in the forest. Dense with Persea borbonia, some very large specimens, with almost no sign of blight. Maritime forest species present: Illex vomitoria (predominant), Vitis rotundifolia (predominant), Ilex opaca (common), Smilax bona-nox (common), Osmanthus americanus (rare), Mitchella repens (rare), Parthenocissus quinquefolia (rare).
locality: Private properties located South of Little River and East of the Intracoastal, on a bluff about 2 mi (3.2 km) wide, and 1 mi (1.6 km) from front of cliff to back cliff, at 30-40 feet elevation.

occurrenceRemarks: [Voucher for U.S. National Science Foundation project, An investigation of the evolution and taxonomy of the true blueberries (Vaccinium section Cyanococcus), DEB-2038213 and DEB-2038217]; Shrub 2.6 m tall, two-stemmed and 15 cm across at base. First year branchlets green with surface trichomes. Vegetative buds green with brown tips, less than 1 mm long and less than 1 mm wide. Leaves 6.5 cm long and 3.5 cm wide, abaxial surface green, dull, with simple trichomes; adaxial surface green to dark green with sheen. Flowers absent. Immature fruit pale green and glossy, 5 mm long (including calyx) and 5 mm wide, with no obvious wax bloom on fruit or calyx; mature fruit not seen. Frequency: rare.
habitat: Deciduous forest along a trail, mid-slope (moderate) to margin of pond in partial to full shade. With Quercus rubra, Quercus muehlenbergii, Acer saccharum, Betula sp., Bryophytes, Vaccinium pallidum, V. stamineum, Gaylussacia baccata. Deciduous litter, duff, and moss substrate with metamorphic rocks scattered throughout. Topographically moist, well-watered; microsite moist.
locality: Westmoreland Sanctuary (260 Chestnut Ridge Rd., Mt Kisco, NY 10549): near pond on new land tract (not yet on trail map), ca. 500 m due N of N edge of Bochtel Lake.

I found three moths, one photographed (I thought the images were in focus when I was taking them), and another was very tine -- maybe 1/4 inch -- and in a weird shape.
